First, let's find the symmetric difference of A and B, denoted as A △ B. The symmetric difference of two sets is the set of elements which are in either of the sets but not in their intersection.

A △ B = (A ∪ B) - (A ∩ B) = {1, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7} - {5} = {1, 3, 4, 6, 7}

Now, let's find the symmetric difference of (A △ B) and C, denoted as (A △ B) △ C.

(A △ B) △ C = ({1, 3, 4, 6, 7} ∪ {3, 4, 5, 7}) - ({1, 3, 4, 6, 7} ∩ {3, 4, 5, 7}) = {1, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7} - {3, 4, 7} = {1, 5, 6}

Now let's find the symmetric difference of B and C, denoted as B △ C.

B △ C = (B ∪ C) - (B ∩ C) = {4, 5, 6, 3, 7} - {4, 5} = {3, 6, 7}

Now, let's find the symmetric difference of A and (B △ C), denoted as A △ (B △ C).

A △ (B △ C) = (A ∪ {3, 6, 7}) - (A ∩ {3, 6, 7}) = {1, 3, 5, 7, 6} - {3, 7} = {1, 5, 6}

So, (A △ B) △ C = {1, 5, 6} and A △ (B △ C) = {1, 5, 6}.
